Disgruntled former Umkhonto weSizwe (MK) combatants are accusing the Umkhonto weSizwe Military Veterans Association (MKMVA) leadership of selling their souls for a piece of silver and allowing themselves to be used in ANC factional battles. ALSO READ: Nearly 80% of the richest 200 in SA are white men The MK combatants are particularly irked by the MKMVA s decision to confer special awards on outgoing Eskom CEO Brian Molefe, SAA chairperson Dudu Myeni and SABC group executive for corporate affairs Hlaudi Motsoeneng, among others. The ceremony, which President Jacob Zuma will preside over, will be held at Emperors Palace, Ekurhuleni, on Thursday. Speaking on behalf of the aggrieved veterans yesterday, Archie Mogodiri said they were gutted to learn that the rich legacy of MK was being abused and rubbished by those who were allegedly desperate for political relevance. Celebrating the achievements of MK and recognising those who selflessly contributed to the liberation of our struggle is a noble thing, Mogodiri said. However, to use these celebrations to further marginalise genuine MK combatants while propping up the credibility of those who, through their misdemeanours, have discredited themselves, is an insult to those who fought against apartheid. ALSO READ: Ramaphosa steps up in race to succeed Zuma This despicable act does not come as a surprise, since some within the current leadership of MKMVA have sold their souls for a piece of silver. MKMVA chairperson Kebby Maphatsoe said the association was, however, recognising people who had helped to transform the economy. It is special category, said Maphatsoe. They are not part of the 31 MK recipients. For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter. For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter. For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter.